You are working on a mobile-first tourist fare estimation app for tricycles in Siquijor, Philippines.

IMPORTANT CONTEXT:
This is NOT a generic maps app.
This is NOT a generic Uber clone.
This is a geographically constrained transport estimation tool.

PRIMARY GOAL:
Help tourists estimate fair tricycle pricing BEFORE entering a tricycle.

CORE PRODUCT PRINCIPLES:

- transparency over fake precision
- believable estimates over perfect simulation
- lightweight infrastructure
- low operational cost
- mobile-first UX
- intuitive interaction

TECH STACK:

- React
- TypeScript
- Vite
- React Leaflet
- Fuse.js
- OpenStreetMap
- OSRM

IMPORTANT CONSTRAINTS:

- avoid paid APIs
- avoid Google APIs
- routing must use road distance
- NEVER use straight-line distance for fares
- preserve modular service-layer architecture

ARCHITECTURE RULES:
Maintain separation between:

- geocoding
- routing
- fare engine
- UI

Do NOT tightly couple:

- map rendering to business logic
- fare calculation to UI
- routing providers to components

SEARCH METHODOLOGY:

- local searchable datasets
- Fuse.js fuzzy search
- Siquijor-only destination scope

ROUTING METHODOLOGY:

- OSRM route engine
- road-based distance calculations
- route polyline rendering

FARE ENGINE METHODOLOGY:
Fare estimates follow layered confidence:

1. Exact official fare match
2. Reverse route match
3. Nearby official route interpolation
4. Distance fallback estimate

Do NOT collapse this into a single simplistic formula.

PRODUCT PHILOSOPHY:
The app should NOT pretend to know exact negotiated real-world pricing.

Instead:

- show confidence
- distinguish official vs estimated
- remain transparent

PREFERRED UX:
“Official Fare”
“Estimated Fare”
“Approximate Tourist Fare”

NOT:
false precision.

CURRENT IMPORTANT TODOs:

- attach real route distances to official fare routes
- improve interpolation calibration
- add fare confidence UI
- add route caching
- improve search ranking
- add aliases/categories
- prepare for PWA support

PERFORMANCE NOTES:

- keep frontend datasets lightweight
- avoid unnecessary rerenders
- mobile performance matters
- avoid heavy dependencies unless justified

WHEN IMPLEMENTING FEATURES:
Prefer:

- reusable services
- typed utility layers
- modular architecture
- composable components

Avoid:

- giant React components
- duplicated logic
- tightly coupled state
- hidden business logic inside UI
